        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "I'm facing this issue, too. I have a workaround: add this to your `init.lua`:\n\n``` lua\nif vim.env.TERM_PROGRAM == \"vscode\" then\n  -- Adjust to match your keyboard layout if necessary\n  local shifted_digits = {\n    [\"<S-1>\"] = '!',\n    [\"<S-2>\"] = '@',\n    [\"<S-3>\"] = '#',\n    [\"<S-4>\"] = '$',\n    [\"<S-5>\"] = '%',\n    [\"<S-6>\"] = '&',\n    [\"<S-7>\"] = '^',\n    [\"<S-8>\"] = '*',\n    [\"<S-9>\"] = '(',\n    [\"<S-0>\"] = ')',\n  }\n\n  for lhs, rhs in pairs(shifted_digits) do\n    vim.keymap.set({ \"n\", \"x\", \"i\" }, lhs, rhs, {\n      noremap = true,\n      silent = true,\n    })\n\n    vim.keymap.set(\"c\", lhs, function()\n      return rhs\n    end, {\n      expr = true,\n      noremap = true,\n    })\n  end\nend\n```\n\nIt's an ugly workaround, but at least it works for the most part until a proper fix is available (doesn't work in `:term` for example, though).\n\nFor what it is worth, I ran this inside Neovim:\n```\n:lua print(vim.fn.keytrans(vim.fn.getcharstr()))\n```\n\nAnd the output from Shift-1 was `1` in any other terminal, but in VS Code it is `<S-1>` (but I guess that is implied by the earlier data).",
